## Level 12 → Level 13
**Objective:** Find the password inside `data.txt` which is a hexdump
of a file that has been repeatedly compressed multiple times.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
mktemp -d                        # created a temporary working directory
                                 # returned: /tmp/tmp.10SqZiKA33
cp data.txt /tmp/tmp.10SqZiKA33  # copied data.txt into temp directory
cd /tmp/tmp.10SqZiKA33           # moved into temp workspace
mv data.txt demo1                # renamed file to work with it freely
xxd -r demo1 > test1             # reversed hexdump → got binary file
file test1                       # gzip compressed data
mv test1 test2.gz                # renamed to .gz for gunzip to accept
gunzip test2.gz                  # decompressed → got test2
file test2                       # bzip2 compressed data
mv test2 test4.bz2               # renamed to .bz2
bzip2 -d test4.bz2               # decompressed → got test4
file test4                       # gzip compressed data
mv test4 test5.gz                # renamed to .gz
gunzip test5.gz                  # decompressed → got test5
file test5                       # POSIX tar archive
tar -xvf test5                   # extracted → got data5.bin
file data5.bin                   # POSIX tar archive
tar -xvf data5.bin               # extracted → got data6.bin
file data6.bin                   # bzip2 compressed data
mv data6.bin test8               # renamed
bzip2 -d test8                   # decompressed → got test8.out
file test8.out                   # POSIX tar archive
mv test8.out test9.tar           # renamed to .tar
tar -xvf test9.tar               # extracted → got data8.bin
file data8.bin                   # gzip compressed data
mv data8.bin test10.gz           # renamed to .gz
gunzip test10.gz                 # decompressed → got test10
file test10                      # ASCII text — final file!
cat test10                       # revealed the password
```

**Full Decompression Chain:**
```
data.txt (hexdump)
    → xxd -r    → binary
    → gunzip    → bzip2
    → bzip2 -d  → gzip
    → gunzip    → tar
    → tar -xvf  → tar
    → tar -xvf  → bzip2
    → bzip2 -d  → tar
    → tar -xvf  → gzip
    → gunzip    → ASCII text (password!)
```

**What I Learned:**
- `xxd -r` reverses a hexdump back into its original binary form
- `mktemp -d` creates a temporary working directory automatically
- Home directory was read only — always use `/tmp` as workspace
- `file` command must be run on every new file before doing anything
- Different compression formats require different tools:

| Format | Detected By `file` | Tool | Command |
|---|---|---|---|
| Hexdump | ASCII text | xxd | `xxd -r file > output` |
| Gzip | gzip compressed data | gunzip | `mv file file.gz` then `gunzip file.gz` |
| Bzip2 | bzip2 compressed data | bzip2 | `mv file file.bz2` then `bzip2 -d file.bz2` |
| Tar | POSIX tar archive | tar | `tar -xvf file` |

**Key Mistakes Made and Lessons Learned:**
- Tried to gunzip a bzip2 file — always check `file` first
- Forgot to redirect `xxd -r` output to a file — prints to screen without `>`
- `gunzip` and `bzip2 -d` refuse files without correct extension —
  always rename using `mv` before decompressing
- `bzip2` without `-d` flag compresses instead of decompressing —
  always use `-d` flag to decompress

**Key Takeaway:**
Always run `file` on every new file before attempting to decompress.
Never assume the compression format — it changes every step and using
the wrong tool wastes time. The workflow for every step is:
`file` → identify format → rename correctly → decompress → repeat.
